As I was driving home after the interview, I recorded some additional information and some comments that follow.

At the end of the interview, Craig and I continued talking, because he took me and showed me all of his medals, and he showed me a bunch of stuff that he had, his pictures and newspaper clippings, and he told me about that...
His buddies, they were very much like a fraternity.
Still today, they could call him up, and he'd do anything in the world for them.
But there's just a bond that's developed, and that he's not ashamed of anything that he did while he was over there.
That what he did is what he had to do, and he doesn't regret or look back upon it.
And that he can't say that he wouldn't do it all over again, because he thinks he would.
My overall impression of this interview was really great.
I was worried when I got there that Mr. Champion wouldn't say a whole lot because he comes across as kind of a shy individual.
But as you can tell, once he started opening up, he just told me about everything.
And as I was leaving, he was talking.
He had gone to A&M for two and a half years.
And he said that

that the people, the guys in the Corps were really, once they found out you had come back from Vietnam, they really tried to get to know you and they really tried, you know, they really wanted to know what it was like since most of them were just about on their way there.
And they really wanted to talk to you about it and they really, you know, that's all they needed to know and they were really after, you know, wanting information.
But
He said he told me about one of the corps commanders that he met, and his last name was Huff.
And he said this boy graduated from school and had just about everything going for him, and he went to Vietnam.
And right before he was to come home, he was shot down in his jet and killed.
And he said, you know,
It's the people like that that he he thinks about that he he still he wonders about a lot of people because he says that this boy had everything going for him and what if

why did it go on so long that if they could have fought it like they would have how many lives could have been saved because they wouldn't still have been there and he looks upon that and he does he blames the people in washington i mean that's who was at fault to him and he says that the people that were
the people that he'll be, like when he's watching a marathon and maybe there's someone in a wheelchair, he wonders about
these kind of people, a young boy who's a good-looking kid who had everything going for him.
And he wonders when.
Was it at the beginning that he lost, that his accident happened, that he lost his legs?
Or was it at the end?
And he said he wonders about how many of the casualties and how many of the wounded could have been avoided if the war would have been ended sooner.
But he also said that out of all his buddies,
You know, they were, he said, you know, it's been 20 years now, he said, since he was in NOM.
He says he still remembers it, and he still often wonders about his buddies that are, you know, that they were close, and a lot of them didn't make it back.
He said, but he still feels like he could call up on the phone someone, one of his buddies, and if he needed something, that they'd do it for him, because you develop such a tight bond.
and he had blacks, there was black and white, and you depended on those people to live.
